Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Quasi-Monte Carlo for a real Bayesian estimation", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"7d07d14c-2983-4f17-be44-0e5dd814e467"],

Cell["\<\
Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] and Halton sequences versus plain Monte Carlo for a \
six-parameter pharmacokinetic inference \[LongDash] measuring the near-1/N \
convergence of quasi-Monte Carlo against Monte Carlo\[CloseCurlyQuote]s 1/\
\[Sqrt]N\
\>", "Subtitle",ExpressionUUID->"c62db285-e9c7-4fce-b935-157fd3ff1b3a"],

Cell["Wolfram Community submission \[LongDash] June 2026", "Subsubtitle",
 FontSlant->Italic,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.4],ExpressionUUID->"e61dbdfe-13ab-40b4-b5d3-773bb32af023"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Abstract", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"ccbb21cb-b468-40e3-8e96-7bfe6d8eeeac"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Almost every number a Bayesian reports \[LongDash] a posterior mean, a \
credible interval, a model evidence, a predicted concentration \[LongDash] is \
an ",
 StyleBox["integral",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " over the parameter space. The default way to evaluate such integrals is \
Monte Carlo (MC) averaging, whose error falls only as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    SuperscriptBox["N", 
     RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "2"}]], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"1b003ae8-e72f-421e-b5d1-431eedda4aec"],
 ": each extra correct digit costs a hundred-fold more samples."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{60, 60}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->14,
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.98, 0.96, 0.9],ExpressionUUID->"dad372fa-f6a5-43f8-b3e1-5823f5264b41"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Quasi-Monte Carlo (QMC)",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " replaces the random sample with a deterministic ",
 StyleBox["low-discrepancy sequence",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " \[LongDash] Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] or Halton points that fill the unit \
cube far more evenly. For smooth integrands the error then falls almost as \
fast as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    SuperscriptBox["N", 
     RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"(", "log", " ", "N", ")"}], "d"], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"a39ab127-55d8-4350-8526-e51131cc8862"],
 " \[LongDash] nearly one full power of ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " better."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{60, 60}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->14,
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.98, 0.96, 0.9],ExpressionUUID->"6ea30f5f-f679-4c7e-9945-72acfa557790"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We put this to work on a genuine inference problem: a ",
 StyleBox["two-compartment pharmacokinetic model",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " (six parameters \[Dash] absorption rate, clearance, two volumes, \
inter-compartmental clearance, residual scatter) fit to the classic ",
 StyleBox["Theophylline",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " data set. We implement Halton and Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] from scratch, \
build the posterior, and measure the convergence of posterior expectations. \
The result is the textbook gap, on real data: MC slopes of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", 
    RowBox[{"-", "0.5"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "2b191257-47ef-4d2b-b41d-35112bf69102"],
 " against Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] slopes of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", 
    RowBox[{"-", "0.95"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"ff3fe52d-62d7-4a9b-a5d6-ea275ba703af"],
 ", and an order-of-magnitude reduction in the number of forward-model solves \
needed for a target accuracy."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{60, 60}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->14,
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.98, 0.96, 0.9],ExpressionUUID->"81e355ec-4a85-4d64-8143-ac1180d220e7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Audience:",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " each section opens with the idea in plain terms, then deepens into the \
equations, the Wolfram Language code, and the measured numbers. Every figure \
is pre-rendered, so the post reads end-to-end without evaluating anything; \
every code cell is runnable if you load the attached package."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{60, 60}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->14,
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.98, 0.96, 0.9],ExpressionUUID->"432d700a-8af2-46eb-beac-d67072b7ea3c"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Setup (optional \[LongDash] only needed if you want to run the code)", \
"Section",ExpressionUUID->"062b92a1-8dad-477b-ae4b-af9cbb462eb3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["You can ignore this section entirely if you just want to read the \
post.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " Every figure is pre-rendered into the notebook as a static image."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"68c9cb67-45f4-4dd6-a37d-b0eae82272d4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If you ",
 StyleBox["do",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " want to run the code, the generators (Halton, Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote]), \
the pharmacokinetic model, the priors, the Laplace posterior, and the \
estimators all live in a single attached package, ",
 StyleBox["qmc_bayes_helpers.wl",
  FontFamily->"Courier"],
 ". Run the cell below once after opening the notebook."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"b6cc958b-8136-4fa4-8303-16a04e3539ff"],

Cell["\<\
(* Put qmc_bayes_helpers.wl in the same folder as this notebook,
   then shift-Enter. *)
SetDirectory[NotebookDirectory[]];
Get[\"qmc_bayes_helpers.wl\"];\
\>", "Input",
 CellMargins->{{60, 30}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->11,ExpressionUUID->"5ec95fa7-0a69-4604-b698-09fe7700f048"],

Cell["\<\
The two cells below define the objects every later section reuses: the prior, \
the real data, the Bayesian problem, and its Laplace\[Dash]Gaussian \
posterior. They are spelled out here so that wherever a later cell calls a \
helper, you can see exactly what was passed in.\
\>", "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"e6a7420c-950b-4fd3-b6a4-7f8aeb0a5e3a"],

Cell["\<\
(* Lognormal-prior hyper-parameters for {ka, CL, V1, Q, V2, sigma}:
   medians and log-scale standard deviations. *)
priorMedians = {1.5, 3.0, 35.0, 2.0, 25.0, 1.0};
priorLogSD   = {0.6, 0.5, 0.5, 0.7, 0.7, 0.5};

(* The real data: Theophylline Subject 1 (single 320 mg oral dose). *)
theoph = LoadTheoph[];
subj1  = SelectSubject[theoph, 1];

(* The Bayesian problem and its Laplace-Gaussian posterior. *)
pkProblem = BayesProblem[subj1[\"dose\"], subj1[\"t\"], subj1[\"c\"],
   priorMedians, priorLogSD];
pkLaplace = LaplacePosterior[pkProblem];\
\>", "Input",
 CellMargins->{{60, 30}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->11,ExpressionUUID->"b48ca4ea-af4a-48c9-b106-bda090bda4b9"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["1.  The problem: averaging, and the square-root wall", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"2a5bd2b7-c728-416d-83df-c59030f0da2e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["The everyday version.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " Suppose you want the average value of some quantity over a \
high-dimensional space \[LongDash] say the mean clearance implied by a \
posterior, or the average rainfall a model predicts. You cannot visit every \
point, so you sample. The Monte Carlo recipe is the obvious one: throw ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " random points, average the values, call it the answer. It always works, in \
any dimension, with no smoothness assumptions. That universality is why it is \
everywhere."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"75ce9a23-50f3-459c-8c16-642ccc53af49"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["The catch.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " The statistical error of an MC average shrinks only as the square root of \
the sample size,"
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"eabced19-5be3-4ef4-af04-2b67eb2f76b0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "MC"], "\[Tilde]", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[Sigma]", "(", "f", ")"}], 
    SqrtBox["N"]], "=", 
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    SuperscriptBox["N", 
     RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "2"}]], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 CellMargins->{{80, 50}, {8, 
  8}},ExpressionUUID->"14fa2451-8e6e-4283-b9a6-1db488c9416e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "so cutting the error by ten needs ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"100", "\[Times]"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"713e0ff7-0deb-4826-8e81-4af2fe629c85"],
 " the samples; one more decimal digit costs a factor of a hundred. When each \
sample is cheap this is merely slow. When each sample requires solving a \
differential equation, running a climate model, or evaluating an expensive \
likelihood, the square-root wall is the whole problem."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"ce4bb44e-4017-4ce2-9744-ca25ffffe061"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Why it is square-root.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " MC error is the standard deviation of a sample mean of ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " independent draws \[LongDash] pure chance cancellation of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[PlusMinus]", TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "fe83ef68-24af-47ac-8e85-11828a4ad51c"],
 " fluctuations. The points know nothing about each other, so they clump and \
leave gaps (left panel of the next figure). Those gaps are wasted \
information. The question QMC asks is simple: ",
 StyleBox["what if we placed the points on purpose, to leave no gaps?",
  FontSlant->Italic]
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"c39c9147-9901-4f2f-8f60-63eefc21a385"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.  Low-discrepancy sequences", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"4fc5bf37-479d-4812-95df-20372912ba7c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A ",
 StyleBox["low-discrepancy sequence",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " is a deterministic set of points engineered to fill ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"[", "0", ",", "1", "]"}], "d"], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"b282821d-1f52-477b-9f5c-f5ba24023022"],
 " as uniformly as possible at every scale. \"Discrepancy\" measures the \
worst mismatch between the fraction of points inside an axis-aligned box and \
the box's volume; low discrepancy means every box holds about its fair share. \
Two classical constructions:"
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"8a841192-d695-47db-b039-e8cab68fe3c3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 StyleBox["Halton",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " (1960). Coordinate ",
 StyleBox["k",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " of the ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 "-th point is the ",
 StyleBox["radical inverse",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " of ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " in the ",
 StyleBox["k",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 "-th prime base \[LongDash] write ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " in base ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " and reflect its digits about the \"decimal\" point. Different primes per \
axis keep the coordinates from lining up."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"90e67ace-bcfd-437b-b7f6-c0cb03847ea0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 StyleBox["Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote]",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " (1967). A ",
 StyleBox["digital (t, m, d)-net",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " in base 2: each coordinate is built from a set of ",
 StyleBox["direction numbers",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " by XOR-ing those selected by the bits of the index. With the right \
direction numbers (we use the Joe\[Dash]Kuo tables) Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] \
points are exceptionally uniform in high dimension."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"afc6d75c-15ac-4192-8379-96798169a8c5"],

Cell["\<\
Both are short to implement. The package builds Halton from radical inverses \
and Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] from Joe\[Dash]Kuo direction numbers via the \
Gray-code/bit-plane construction; here we just ask for the points:\
\>", "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"89d61281-bf13-4e53-983d-83e0ef895177"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
(* 256 points of each kind in 2-D. *)
mc  = LDPoints[\"MonteCarlo\", 256, 2];
hal = LDPoints[\"Halton\", 256, 2];
sob = LDPoints[\"Sobol\", 256, 2];
GraphicsRow[ListPlot[#, AspectRatio -> 1, Frame -> True,
     PlotRange -> {{0, 1}, {0, 1}}, ImageSize -> 230] & /@ {mc, hal, sob}]\
\>", "Input",
 CellMargins->{{60, 30}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->11,ExpressionUUID->"3145511d-9cbc-41bf-98fd-23bcefc40f08"],

