Cell[TextData[{
 "Figure 5.1  RMSE versus ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " (log-log) for two posterior expectations of the real Theophylline fit. ",
 StyleBox["Left:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " posterior mean clearance (analytic reference). ",
 StyleBox["Right:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " posterior-predictive concentration at 6 h (each evaluation a forward model \
solve). Monte Carlo follows the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["N", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "2"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"2c34e3b5-e401-4c42-8179-a60005488886"],
 " guide (slope \[TildeTilde] ",
 StyleBox["-0.50",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 "); Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] and Halton follow ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["N", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "c300f7a3-073e-48df-8b13-91332058614c"],
 " (slopes \[TildeTilde] ",
 StyleBox["-0.95",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 "). At ",
 StyleBox["N = 32768",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] is roughly 50\[Times] more accurate than MC, and \
the gap widens with ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{70, 70}, {2, 14}},
 FontSize->11,
 FontSlant->Italic,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.35],ExpressionUUID->"167e0cb6-cca1-454c-a8da-64856b79a6c4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "That is the headline result of the project, and it is on real data: the \
same number of model evaluations buys you almost twice as many correct digits \
with Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] as with Monte Carlo. The Halton curve sits just \
above Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] \[LongDash] both achieve the near-",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["N", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "d3737fb6-1b9b-4763-a927-56945cef7357"],
 " rate, with Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] the more uniform in six dimensions."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"a9817361-5797-465f-91b6-234fcb55e888"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["6.  Dimension dependence: why the advantage erodes", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"77378bbe-6339-41be-bb7a-5f84b002c6ba"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The QMC rate carries a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"(", "log", " ", "N", ")"}], "d"], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"0b54f057-0dd3-432b-99ad-4ec91b159359"],
 " factor, and that factor is not cosmetic: as the dimension ",
 StyleBox["d",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " grows, the advantage over Monte Carlo erodes, because filling a \
high-dimensional cube evenly gets exponentially harder. The cleanest way to \
see it is to fix the sampling budget ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " and ask how many times more accurate Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] is than MC \
\[LongDash] the ",
 StyleBox["efficiency gain",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " \[LongDash] as the dimension climbs. We use a smooth product integrand \
with exact integral 1:"
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"f1df5444-9bad-4a11-8b08-000f52dd0b23"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
(* Smooth product integrand, exact integral = 1. Efficiency gain
   (MC RMSE / Sobol' RMSE) at fixed budget N, across dimension d. *)
cAmp  = 0.6;
fMean = Function[pts, Mean[Times @@@ (1 + cAmp Cos[2 Pi pts])]];
rmseAt[method_, d_, n_] := Sqrt@Mean@Table[
   (fMean[RandomizedLDPoints[method, n, d, 53 r + d]] - 1.)^2, {r, 120}];
gain[n_] := Table[rmseAt[\"MonteCarlo\", d, n]/rmseAt[\"Sobol\", d, n], {d, \
2, 12}];
{gain[4096], gain[65536]}\
\>", "Input",
 CellMargins->{{60, 30}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->11,ExpressionUUID->"de0a1ed1-4afc-4b5b-800e-7ad53a9757f7"],

