Cell[TextData[{
 "Figure 8.1  Forward-model solves required to reach a given accuracy on the \
posterior-predictive concentration. Because Monte Carlo needs ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    SuperscriptBox["tol", 
     RowBox[{"-", "2"}]], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"7584c82c-06c4-4e96-83e3-0b98c7399357"],
 " evaluations while QMC needs ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    SuperscriptBox["tol", 
     RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"e08f4b33-2e48-4393-9e42-b488108bc80d"],
 ", the gap widens as you demand more accuracy: Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] is \
about 2\[Times] cheaper at 1% accuracy, 4\[Times] at 0.5%, and roughly 18\
\[Times] at 0.1%. When each evaluation is an expensive ODE solve, that is the \
difference between an overnight run and a coffee break."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{70, 70}, {2, 14}},
 FontSize->11,
 FontSlant->Italic,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.35],ExpressionUUID->"85096929-f14a-49ab-bdf8-0d5979e4d63c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This is the whole value proposition in one figure. QMC does not change what \
you compute \[LongDash] same posterior, same estimand, same code structure \
\[LongDash] it changes only ",
 StyleBox["which points you evaluate at",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 ", and that single swap buys back most of an order of magnitude (often more) \
in model runs."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"8623a75e-9044-45eb-a45e-c5e170886a7e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["9.  Conclusions and caveats", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"611741fd-c119-49a2-b78a-c164f1b3ba1c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "On a genuine six-parameter pharmacokinetic inference from the Theophylline \
data, deterministic low-discrepancy sampling beats plain Monte Carlo by close \
to a full power of ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 ": measured slopes of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", 
    RowBox[{"-", "0.95"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"0ef7418c-926c-432d-b3f2-4333ea5b8a46"],
 " for Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] and Halton against ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[TildeTilde]", 
    RowBox[{"-", "0.5"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "b3843f80-1d89-4b3b-beba-337a46c17d6e"],
 " for MC, and an order-of-magnitude saving in forward-model solves at the \
accuracies that matter."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"5b196402-a283-4ed8-8f06-47bd21991376"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["When QMC helps, and when it does not.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " The gains are real when (i) the dimension is low-to-moderate or the \
effective dimension is small; (ii) the integrand is smooth, i.e. of bounded \
variation; and (iii) evaluations are the bottleneck. They evaporate when the \
integrand is rough or discontinuous (indicator functions, hard thresholds), \
when the dimension is very large, or when an importance-sampling weight is \
heavy-tailed \[LongDash] which is exactly why we integrate against a smooth \
Gaussianized posterior rather than a spiky importance ratio."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"cf59946b-d187-495f-90be-760a6385aa79"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Reproducing the rate in your own work.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " The recipe is portable: (1) reparameterize to an unconstrained space and \
build a Gaussian (Laplace) approximation of the posterior; (2) map the unit \
cube through it with the inverse-CDF transform; (3) replace your \
pseudo-random draws with a randomized Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] or Halton set; \
(4) average over a few randomizations to get an error bar. Steps 1\[Dash]2 \
are standard Bayesian asymptotics; steps 3\[Dash]4 are a two-line change to \
existing code."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"16d344f5-75af-49cb-a3ca-0727205195ef"]
}, Open  ]],

